      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nIn the year <htdate0>, information reaches us from countless sources and in overwhelming quantities. Given this reality, we must engage in three key reflections:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "now",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: On Sources</b><br /><br />Is every source of information reliable?<br /><br />Is the correct information simply what appeals to us, or must it be grounded in evidence?<br /><br />How can we verify a source’s credibility?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "*History Tracers* uses four types of sources—primary, reference, religious, and even social media—all of which are explained in detail within this text.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_primary_source",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Primary Sources\n\nThis is the main source of information used by History Tracers. Its greater credibility compared to other sources stems from being written contemporaneously with the events described (<htcite0>), or because they represent first-collected scientific data that can be independently verified and replicated (<htcite1>).\n\n#### Examples\n\nExamples of primary sources include:\n- **Genetic testing**: While each person's DNA is unique, certain segments are shared among humans and even with other species (<htcite2>; <htcite3>).\n- **Personal documents**: Records containing individuals' names and sometimes those of their immediate ancestors.\n-**Chronicles**: Firsthand descriptions of historical events written by **contemporaries**.\n- **Language dictionaries**: As word meanings evolve over time, historical dictionaries help understand contemporary usage (<htcite4>; <htcite5>; <htcite6>).\n- **Specialized dictionaries**: Certain fields maintain specific terminology, such as the *Diccionario de Genealogía* by Gilber Rubim Rangel (<htcite7>; <htcite8>; <htcite9>).\n- **Government documents**: These vary by era and administration. **Figure 1** shows a page from the Treaty of Tordesillas as an example.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0eff7270-c6b4-4bab-b685-67d3c2970a93",
