      {
         "id": "SECTION_references",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### References\n\nIn *History Tracers*, we classify references into two categories of texts:\n- **Secondary sources**: Texts that cite documented data from primary sources, including academic theses, books, and scientific articles (<htcite0>).\n- **General texts**: These works may reference other publications or individuals but typically lack substantive evidentiary support for their claims. Many ancient genealogical records (nobiliaries) fall into this category.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3ec8a96e-09c1-4241-891a-db9476761232",
                     "text": "Ajayi, V. O.",
                     "page": "pp. 2, 4",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2017",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "section_religious",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Religious Sources\n\nThis section examines religious texts that serve as foundational belief systems for many people.\n\nWhen referencing these sources, we will always maintain respect for personal beliefs while applying a methodology grounded in the natural world and measurable evidence. Furthermore, we will specifically highlight when these sources contain verifiable historical data.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_sn",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Social Media\n\nSocial media has become an integral part of our lives, and History Tracers utilizes these platforms to disseminate new texts and democratize knowledge. However, we cannot overlook an important reflection by Umberto Eco",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "97ad972d-e3f9-443a-9038-965df6c99fd5",
                     "text": "Calvillo, J., & Martínez, C. E. A.",
                     "page": "pp. 186 ",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul class=\"citation\"><li><i>\"...The tragedy of the Internet is that it has promoted the village idiot as the bearer of truth.\"</i></li> </ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Precisely because social medias are platforms where unsubstantiated texts and videos proliferate, they occupy the lowest position in our source hierarchy.\n\nWe must acknowledge that many individuals are doing excellent scientific outreach work on these platforms. When we reference their publications, we properly cite them in our *References* section.\n\nWe understand that the \"idiot\" Eco refers to represents individuals who either: Lack access to adequate information, or were educated to memorize rather than think critically. Our mission is to help move beyond this self-proclaimed \"truth-teller\" mentality and foster genuine critical thinking skills.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusions",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Conclusion\n\nThis text has presented the sources used by History Tracers and their connection to the natural world.\n\nWe recommend that whenever these sources are referenced and the original language is accessible, researchers should consult them directly (through reading or viewing, in the case of audiovisual materials) to gain deeper understanding of the subject matter.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
